Release Incanter 1.5.5

use correct parameter names for gamma distribution functions

Incanter used the 'rate' as parameter name, although in reality this was
a 'scale' parameter (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gamma_distribution).
For pdf-gamma, cdf-gamma & sample-gamma functions the new parameter
':scale' was introduced (equivalent to the old ':rate' parameter), and
':rate' parameter is now the '1/:scale'...

Also, the arguments of Probability/gamma wasn't used in correct order...

Merge pull request #98 from MarkSwanson/group-on-filter-fn

ISSUE 96: (in liebke's branch) The clojure compiler was confusing the

incanter.io/read-dataset reads on a per-line basis

read-dataset used CSVReader.readAll which parsed the whole file at once.
In case of larger CSV files it caused some major headaches for the GC. This
patch makes CSVReader work on a per-line basis by using CSVReader.read and
fully parsing each line before moving to a next one.

A following benchmark was used to measure effects of this patch. 1k.csv is
a 1k lines long dataset with 700 numerical features. It's around 1.7MB.

    cat <<EOF | JAVA_OPTS=-Xmx100M incanter
    (do
      (use '(incanter io core))
      (time
        (doall (map
                 (fn [_]
                     (nrow (incanter.io/read-dataset "1k.csv")))
                 (range 5)))))
    EOF

Original read-dataset needed 13.5 seconds. Profiling showed that a
significant part of this time was spent in GC. This patch reduces
execution time to 7.3s by significantly reducing the number of String
and char[] instances stored simultaneously on the heap. Memory consumption
is reduced as well.

It's also worth mentioning that when 1k.csv aws replaced with a 3 times
larger 3k.csv the original read-dataset ran out of memory. This patch
solves the problem.

Signed-off-by: Jan Stępień <jstepien@users.sourceforge.net>

charts function and options clean up

formalizes on :title option by removing :main-title ambiguity

While doing this I noticed many on the macros were setting the
:main-title option even though it was never being used (:title really
    was).  The only underlying function that was using :main-title
instead of :title was xy-plot*.  By formalizing on :title the function
and macro options are the same and should prevent confusion.

now have a one-to-one function* version that can be used outside the ns.

range of values. Sampler is reasonably efficient (probability of

protocol extends the PersistentVector class so that [:foo :bar :foo],
for example becomes a distribution.
